course_name: Foundations of Western Art: Prehistoric to Renaissance
description: Mediterranean and European art and architecture presented in historical, cultural and social context that introduces art history as a discipline.
An introduction to the major art forms and monuments of religious art in India, Southeast Asia, China and Japan from prehistory to1300.

course_name: America, the Frontier, and the New West
description: Introduction to an interdisciplinary study of American political, cultural and social life with a particular emphasis on the Western United States as a region. Recommended preparation: HIST 200, ENGL 263

course_name: Native Americans in American Public Life
description: Role of Native Americans in American public life from colonial times to the present; Native American societies and governments and their relations to the U.S.
Ancient Roman values, ideas, and institutions of relevance to later periods of civilization.

course_name: Classical Mythology in Art and Literature
description: Classical Greek and Roman mythology as inspiration for literature, art, music, and film in various historical contexts.

course_name: Masterpieces and Masterminds: Literature and Thought
description: A broad introduction to the great works of Western culture from antiquity to 1800.
Introduction to African cultural history by way of a comparative study of major literary works and intellectual thought from representative regions and countries in Africa.
Theories of communication and persuasion in ancient Greece and Rome; cultural and social contexts of classical rhetorical theory; major historical figures and concepts.

course_name: Histories of Art, Design and Visual Culture
description: A loosely chronological, thematic survey of art, visual culture, design, and critical theory from the early modern period through modernism (1500 1950).

course_name: International and Historical Perspectives on Dance
description: Exploration of dance as an art form in its artistic, political, and socio-cultural climate. Studies of the continuum of dance within its historical context.

description: Introduction to the major humanities traditions of China, Japan, and Korea through an examination of representative works drawnfrom literature, aesthetics, philosophy, religion, and historicalwriting.
Japanese literature from the earliest times to the present; development of prose, poetry and the novel; evolution of theatre; Japanese literature under Western influence. Conducted in English.

course_name: Korean Culture from Ancient to Modern Times
description: The history of Korean literature and culture from the ancient to the modern era. Recommended preparation: HIST 105g.
Characteristics and aspects of Chinese civilization;interpretation of philosophy, literature, religion, art, music.Conducted in English.
Main patterns of change in modern China, Japan, and Korea;historical framework and the insights of geography, economics,political science, and other disciplines.

A thematic approach to California history from precontact to present; focus on peoples, environment, economic, social, and cultural development, politics, and rise to global influence.
Business history of East Asia (China, Japan, Korea, Taiwan, and Hong Kong) as related to culture, politics, and society.
Major ideas, personalities, and movements in Jewish history from antiquity to the present in light of the interaction of the Jews with the general culture.
Jewish beliefs, practices, and history from the biblical period to the present; Judaic contributions to Western civilization.

course_name: Fundamentals of the U.S. Legal System
description: Introduces the U.S. legal system and its relationship to basic principles of the rule of law. Examines lawmaking institutions, judicial processes and contemporary legal issues.

course_name: Power and Authority in the Middle East
description: A comparative examination of social relations of power and institutions with a special focus on intellectual traditions, the law, and social movements.

Survey of the changing beliefs and practices of the Christian religion from its origins through early modernity (100 CE - 1500 CE), with special attention to different varieties of Christian literature.

course_name: Islamic Spirituality: Mysticism and the Sufi Tradition
description: Examination of the origins, development, and basic concepts and practices of Sufism, as well as its relationship to other areas of Islamic life.

course_name: The History and Geography of Drugs
description: Global perspectives; discovery and use of drugs (legal/illegal); poisons. How they helped shape, modify or change history as described in classical literature through present day.
Russian cultural identity from its beginnings until today. The Eastern Orthodox tradition, its traumatic confrontation with Western culture, and their continuous interaction.

course_name: Introduction to Latin American and Iberian Studies
description: Introduction to the cultural history of Spain, Portugal and Latin America with a focus on literature and visual works from the early-modern period to the twenty-first century.
Emergence of feminist thought from the Enlightenment to the present; historical development of female subjectivity; advancement of womens rights; feminisms from alternative ideological perspectives.
